    "name": "The Penny Press",
    "summary": "The Penny Press refers to inexpensive, mass-produced newspapers that emerged in the United States during the early 1830s. These papers revolutionized journalism by focusing on daily events, human-interest stories, and sensationalism, catering to a broader audience. The affordability of a penny made them accessible to the working class, expanding readership and changing the funding model to rely more on advertising revenue than subscriptions. This democratization of news led to increased public awareness and participation in societal issues, laying the groundwork for modern journalism.",
